Here's how to implement all three:

**1 & 2. Guard navigation in `AppShell.xaml.cs`** — use `GetDeferral()` for the async dialog:

```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    if (args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop
        && Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page
        && page.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.CurrentPage.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

**3. Custom "Cancel" back button** — add this inside your `EditProductPage.xaml`:

```xml
<ContentPage ...>
    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                           Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
    <!-- rest of your page -->
</ContentPage>
```

The `CancelCommand` in your ViewModel just navigates back (the guard will intercept it):

```csharp
[RelayCommand]
async Task Cancel()
{
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

**Key points:**
- `GetDeferral()` is required because `DisplayAlert` is async — without it the navigation completes before the dialog returns.
- `args.Cancel()` prevents the navigation when the user chooses "Stay".
- `ShellNavigationSource.Pop` targets only back-navigation, so forward navigation is unaffected.
- `TextOverride="Cancel"` replaces the default back arrow text on the navigation bar.
